You are correct that our active directory is instance by instance, And =
yes the work we are doing at the moment is adding a SAML layer / server =
on top of our front end which is vendor neutral. (Think Amazon=E2=80=99s =
SSO is aimed at firms with lots of different apps that all need =
integrating with the same customer at the same time =E2=80=93 maybe, =
still don=E2=80=99t really get it).

I also want to use the SSO to cover the scheme portal (there is one =
logon per scheme to allow us to change some of the static data quicker =
than using the API) so trying to work out how we handle that. Probably =
get ourselves a PING identity account and initially manually create our =
scheme users in Ping Identity, possibly moving to a active directory =
later.

C

=20

From: Josh Klein <josh@josh.is>=20
Sent: 08 August 2020 10:38
To: chris@indigometrics.com
Subject: Re: Update

=20

Isn=E2=80=99t our active directory instance by instance? I.e., the front =
end instance is our sole integration with customers, meaning each =
instance is a separate active directory, each of which can have a SSO =
integration for the client. If that=E2=80=99s the case, having a =
=E2=80=9Cvendor neutral=E2=80=9D SSO saves us a lot of trouble, no? What =
am I missing?

=20

- J

=20

=20

On Fri, Aug 7, 2020 at 2:40 PM <chris@indigometrics.com =
<mailto:chris@indigometrics.com> > wrote:

J,

=20

An update on the thrilling subject of single sign on:

=20

Plan is for:

*	Liquid to add the SAML server on top of our application
*	I now have a Ping Identity account which I have populated with 5 users =
(manually =E2=80=93 you can also map it to an active directory) and will =
mimic Bechtel to test
*	I have therefore given Liquid the metadata of my Ping Identity Account =
and they are going to use that to get the handoff working
*	We are still not really sure as to how it works so we are going to try =
and see what happens! i.e. when we ask Ping Identity for ID verification =
what exactly does it show the user and what data does it pass back to us
*	Going forward any new customers would need to do the configuration =
that we are doing at the moment which involves exchanging meta data =
files and various other bits and pieces
*	Still not really sure what AWS Single Sign on does for us in =
practicality. I get it if we were running our active directory on AWS =
but because we aren=E2=80=99t it seems that all AWS single sign on does =
for us is to make it easier to make the SAML setup / connection

=20

C


